{"title_count": 0, "title": "CMO Today: Facebook Curbs Data Broker Information Sharing; Turner CEO Testimony; Strong \u2018Roseanne\u2019 Ratings", "text": "Good morning. For some people, deleting Facebook is a psychological roller coaster akin to the five stages of grief: denial; anger; bargaining; depression; then, finally, acceptance. WSJ follows the paths of people who have gone Facebook cold turkey amid the #DeleteFacebook movement. It reveals the complicated relationship many of us have with the social-networking site.\n\nIt wouldn\u2019t be a March CMO Today newsletter without leading on the latest twist in Facebook\u2019s Cambridge Analytica fallout. Facebook announced Wednesday that it will curb the information it exchanges with data brokers, such as Acxiom, Oracle Data Cloud and Experian, Business Insider first reported. Specifically, it\u2019s shutting down its \u201cPartner Categories\u201d tool, which let advertisers use data from these brokers to target consumers based on their offline behavior, such as people in the market for a luxury car, credit-card holders or frequent shampoo buyers. Acxiom said that could hurt its fiscal 2019 revenue and profit by as much as $25 million, WSJ reported. Furthermore, people familiar with the matter say Facebook will end its practice of providing anonymized data from its platform to data brokers, which is used to measure the effectiveness of their ad campaigns\u2014although the social network is looking to find more secure ways to share data for ad measurement purposes. Remember, Facebook isn\u2019t reacting just to the Cambridge Analytica data-sharing hubbub: Like every other company, it\u2019s also preparing for Europe\u2019s General Data Protection Regulation.\n\n\u2014What It Means for Marketers\u2014\n\nIt all depends on which category your brand is in. As Rob Blackie, an independent digital strategist, explained to me, Facebook may have reams of data, but there\u2019s a lot of information missing that certain marketers\u2014in categories such as automotive or consumer goods\u2014find extremely useful for audience segmentation. \u201cFacebook has loads of data about the sort of thing you talk about on Facebook, such as your football team. With sports, people leave a huge data trail, but [working out a person\u2019s] income is really hard because people don\u2019t talk about it or leave strong signals.\u201d That\u2019s where the brokers came in, collecting data from sources including loyalty programs, census data and surveys. Perhaps Facebook\u2019s loss could be Amazon\u2019s gain. The e-commerce giant has direct access to its own unique data on how people shop, which helps advertisers refine their targeting for ads on Amazon.com and the rest of the web. And it has the kind of reach advertisers desire.\n\nJohnny B Goode\n\nTurner CEO John Martin took to the stand again in the AT&T-Time Warner and Department of Justice antitrust trial Wednesday and detailed how the proposed merger would help the companies better compete against Google and Facebook, Variety reported. \u201cWe are not even playing the same arena,\u201d said Mr. Martin, commenting on the duopoly\u2019s dominance of the ad market. He reiterated the argument that AT&T\u2019s treasure trove of data on its mobile users would give Time Warner\u2019s Turner \u201ca tremendous head start\u201d when it comes to building a data-driven advertising targeting model, rather than relying on broader demographic information and dayparts. That\u2019ll give Turner\u2019s ads more value as the network looks to reduce its ad load. And Turner is looking for more data to prove people actually watch the advertising it airs, with Mr. Martin repeating the often-cited John Wanamaker line about knowing half of your ad dollars are wasted, but just not knowing which half. Thursday\u2019s festivities will feature testimony from MIT professor John Hauser and Comcast executive Greg Rigdon, time allowing.\n\nRoseanne (Put On Your Red Light)\n\nTV ratings stories in recent years have usually been doom and gloom analyses about the impact of cord-cutting on linear TV. Not so for ABC\u2019s revival of \u201cRoseanne,\u201d which brought in a huge 18.2 million viewers for the season 10 premiere Tuesday, according to Nielsen. Three big stats from CNN to put that figure into context: 1) Tuesday\u2019s show scored the highest rating for the 18 to 49 demographic for any comedy telecast since 2014. 2) The only scripted show to have a bigger audience this season was the episode of NBC\u2019s \u201cThis Is Us\u201d that aired after the Super Bowl and brought in 26.9 million viewers. 3) Tuesday night\u2019s episode racked up 10% more viewers than the original show\u2019s finale 21 years ago. Even President Donald Trump was impressed and reportedly personally called the show\u2019s creator and star, Roseanne Barr, to congratulate her on the ratings triumph. In the reboot, Roseanne Conner is a Trump supporter, as is Ms. Barr. \u201cHollywood is now faced with indisputable evidence that there\u2019s a huge potential audience out there for programs that don\u2019t actively insult 63 million Trump voters,\u201d John Podhoretz wrote for the New York Post.\n\nI Don\u2019t Like Cricket\n\nAustralia\u2019s national cricket team sent three players home from their South Africa tour on Saturday for their role in a ball-tampering incident on day three of the third Test. It\u2019s cricket\u2019s \u201cDeflategate\u201d moment, and, unsurprisingly, many sponsors have ripped up their deals with the players involved. More unusual, though, is Magellan Financial Group\u2019s move to terminate its three-year contract (which only began in August 2017) with Cricket Australia as the naming rights sponsor of the Australian Men\u2019s Domestic Test Series. \u201cI\u2019ve never seen an event sponsor do this before, and never as quickly, not even close,\u201d sports marketing consultant Tim Crow told me. What\u2019s different from other scandals (Lance Armstrong, Tiger Woods, doping), he said, is that there has been \u201cuniversal condemnation of the team\u201d in Australia\u2014from ordinary people, not just from headline writers and hard-core sports fans. For corporates, sponsorships have moved beyond badging exercises to an opportunity to \u201cproject their values,\u201d and Magellan\u2019s move \u201cis a real sign of how important this is becoming,\u201d Mr. Crow said.\n\nBest of the rest\n\nApple CEO Tim Cook has called for more privacy regulation, saying consumers should have more visibility into the personal information they share online and how companies use that data to build profiles of those users. [WSJ]\n\nWalmart is pulling Cosmopolitan from its checkout aisles, following a long campaign targeting the magazine for its \u201chyper-sexualized\u201d content. In a statement, Walmart said, \u201cWhile this was primarily a business decision, the concerns raised were heard. [NPR]\n\nTrade group the Advertising Research Foundation gave an award to Cambridge Analytica last year for the research firm\u2019s \u201cbig data\u201d work during the 2016 presidential election. Now the ARF plans to work with other industry groups to form new guidelines for collecting and protecting user information. [New York Times]\n\nThe number of over-the-top-only U.S. households has tripled since 2013 to 14.1 million homes, or 11% of all U.S. TV households. [Adweek]\n\nAMC Networks is launching a team to sell data products to advertisers. [Variety]\n\nRender Media, the owner of Cooking Panda and Opposing Views, is the latest digital publisher to shut down after Facebook\u2019s algorithm changes. [CMO Today]\n\nHavas Group has launched \u201cHavas Blockchain,\u201d which will offer international communications services to initial coin offering and blockchain products. [PR Week]\n\nAbout Us\n\nFollow us on Twitter: @wsjCMO, @larakiara, @VranicaWSJ, @alexbruell,@BenMullin, @srabil, @asharma\n\nSubscribe to our morning newsletter, delivered straight to your inbox, at http://on.wsj.com/CMOTodaySignup.\n\nWrite to Lara O\u2019Reilly at lara.oreilly@wsj.com", "company": "amazon", "authors": ["Lara O Reilly", "Lara.Oreilly Wsj.Com"], "tokens": ["good", "morning", ".", "for", "some", "people", ",", "deleting", "facebook", "is", "a", "psychological", "roller", "coaster", "akin", "to", "the", "five", "stages", "of", "grief", ":", "denial", ";", "anger", ";", "bargaining", ";", "depression", ";", "then", ",", "finally", ",", "acceptance", ".", "wsj", "follows", "the", "paths", "of", "people", "who", "have", "gone", "facebook", "cold", "turkey", "amid", "the", "#", "deletefacebook", "movement", ".", "it", "reveals", "the", "complicated", "relationship", "many", "of", "us", "have", "with", "the", "social-networking", "site", ".", "it", "wouldn", "\u2019", "t", "be", "a", "march", "cmo", "today", "newsletter", "without", "leading", "on", "the", "latest", "twist", "in", "facebook", "\u2019", "s", "cambridge", "analytica", "fallout", ".", "facebook", "announced", "wednesday", "that", "it", "will", "curb", "the", "information", "it", "exchanges", "with", "data", "brokers", ",", "such", "as", "acxiom", ",", "oracle", "data", "cloud", "and", "experian", ",", "business", "insider", "first", "reported", ".", "specifically", ",", "it", "\u2019", "s", "shutting", "down", "its", "\u201c", "partner", "categories", "\u201d", "tool", ",", "which", "let", "advertisers", "use", "data", "from", "these", "brokers", "to", "target", "consumers", "based", "on", "their", "offline", "behavior", ",", "such", "as", "people", "in", "the", "market", "for", "a", "luxury", "car", ",", "credit-card", "holders", "or", "frequent", "shampoo", "buyers", ".", "acxiom", "said", "that", "could", "hurt", "its", "fiscal", "2019", "revenue", "and", "profit", "by", "as", "much", "as", "$", "25", "million", ",", "wsj", "reported", ".", "furthermore", ",", "people", "familiar", "with", "the", "matter", "say", "facebook", "will", "e