{"title_count": 1, "title": "CMO Today: WhatsApp CEO Leaving Facebook; Publishers Protest Google GDPR Policy; Next Steps For Amazon\u2019s Ad Business", "text": "Good morning. Facebook\u2019s F8 annual developer conference takes place today and Wednesday in San Jose. The social network restricted developer access to many its APIs in the wake of its Cambridge Analytica scandal, so the tone might be more conciliatory this time around. The schedule suggests there\u2019ll be lots of topics Tuesday for marketers to pay attention to, including a session on \u201cwhy bidding matters,\u201d updates to Facebook app ads and a section on building your video business.\n\nHow\u2019s this for timing? On the eve of F8, the Washington Post reported the billionaire chief executive of WhatsApp, Jan Koum, is planning to leave Facebook. He sold the messaging app to Facebook for more than $19 billion in 2014. Mr. Koum, who also reportedly plans to leave Facebook\u2019s board of directors, apparently clashed with Facebook\u2019s executives over its strategy to share data across Facebook\u2019s platforms and its end-to-end encryption policy. You might remember WhatsApp co-founder Brian Acton left the company late last year, then quickly endorsed the #DeleteFacebook campaign. Both Mr. Koum and Mr. Acton weren\u2019t the biggest advocates of advertising, writing in a 2012 blog post that ads were a \u201cdisruption to aesthetics, an insult to your intelligence, and the interruption of your train of thought.\u201d (Tell us how you really feel!) One wonders whether, without WhatsApp\u2019s resistant founders, Facebook may now find it easier to introduce ad products to the messaging app. Indeed, the WSJ reports Mr. Koum\u2019s departure followed an internal debate about introducing ads to WhatsApp\u2019s \u201cStatus\u201d feature.\n\nOh, We\u2019re Not Gonna Take It\n\nBack in March I reported Google was asking its publisher partners to get consent on its behalf to gather data on European users and target ads using its popular ad-tech tools once the forthcoming General Data Protection Regulation comes into force in May. Among the requirements, Google wants publishers to accept it is a \u201cco-controller\u201d of their users\u2019 data, rather than a \u201cprocessor,\u201d under the GDPR rules. Some publishers aren\u2019t best-pleased with those suggestions. Ad Age reports four U.S. trade associations\u2014Digital Content Next, European Publishers Council, News Media Alliance and the News Media Association\u2014released a letter Monday addressed to Google CEO Sundar Pichai, criticizing the company\u2019s GDPR policy. The letter reprimands Google for waiting \u201cuntil the last-minute\u201d to announce the proposals, which the trade groups say \u201cundermine the fundamental purposes of the GDPR.\u201d In response, Google says it always asked publishers to get user consent for the use of its ad tech on their sites and said operating as a \u201ccontroller\u201d won\u2019t give the company any more rights to publisher data than before.\n\nAutomatic Love\n\nAmazon\u2019s ad business has quietly grown into a multi-billion dollar revenue beast. To help get more ad dollars flowing through its platforms, Amazon plans to lean heavily on automated, self-service offerings, according to this detailed piece from Ad Age\u2019s Garrett Sloane. While Amazon still intends to run a premium managed-service offering for its top clients, the e-commerce company is busy building out its programmatic tools. Ad Age\u2019s sources say Amazon is running a test with some brands and their agencies to tag ads with a pixel to track whether their ads running outside Amazon properties lead to sales on the e-commerce site. Amazon is also reportedly building a video ad platform, similar to what Roku offers, for its Fire TV device. On the sell-side, Ad Age says Amazon is \u201cundercutting Google [DoubleClick for Publishers] on ad-tech fees\u201d to recruit more publishers for its Amazon Publisher Services and offering to spend its own ad dollars\u2014promoting its original shows from Prime, for example\u2014on their sites if they sign up for its marketplace. As Amazon continues to move its way up the media plan, expect to see lots more Amazon-specialist agencies popping up, offering to help marketers get their heads around its growing portfolio of ad services.\n\nSisters Are Doin\u2019 It For Themselves\n\nTwitter said during its first-quarter earnings last month that video accounts for more than half of its revenue. Hoping to build on that momentum, Twitter is exploring whether to let publishers sell pre-roll ads that run at the start of their video clips on the platform themselves, CMO Today\u2019s Ben Mullin reports. Just as with Facebook\u2019s Instant Articles format or Snap\u2019s Discover, giving publishers the option to sell Twitter pre-rolls would allow them the opportunity to pitch marketers broader ad packages across a range of different platforms. The new offering, which is still in development, doesn\u2019t look as though it would change the financial split of ad sales Twitter keeps, a person familiar with the matter said. Currently publishers keep 70% of the revenue from ads sold against their Twitter content. Elsewhere in Twitter news, the company held its NewFront event Monday night. Twitter touted its positioning around \u201clive,\u201d and particularly live video. As Broadcasting and Cable reported, Twitter announced 30-plus content deals and renewals at the presentation, including tie-ups with NBCUniversal, ESPN and Viacom.\n\nBest of the rest\n\nThe New York Times is making a big push into television, having signed a deal with Anonymous Content earlier this year. The newspaper is looking to create a show similar to its popular \u201cThe Daily\u201d podcast and programs around other popular content, such as its \u201cModern Love\u201d column, the company said at its NewFront presentation on Monday. [Ad Age]\n\nWhy Amazon has found it difficult gaining traction in the apparel and footwear categories in Europe. [WSJ]\n\nA look at the struggles facing digital-specialist ad agencies. [Digiday]\n\nFacebook plans to \u201creduce the visual prominence\u201d of fake news stories in the mobile news feed by making them show up as smaller than accurate news links. [TechCrunch]\n\nWPP has taken full ownership of a handful of agencies in the Asia-Pacific region in a share swap with Dentsu, for an undisclosed price. The deal includes WPP taking full control of the Y&R and Wunderman joint-venture agency assets across Southeast Asia and in Taiwan, plus Dentsu Sudler & Hennessey in Japan. Meanwhile, Dentsu has acquired full control of Dentsu Y&R and Wunderman Dentsu in Japan. [MarketWatch]\n\nInternet-radio service Pandora carried out a study that found that higher ad loads can push users to pay for an ad-free version. But subscriptions don\u2019t make up for the lost ad revenue from those who listen less or leave the service altogether. [Wired]\n\nAt the BBC News NewFront, the British broadcaster pushed its global reach and \u201ctrust factor.\u201d The company said it has access to 450 million households with BBC World News a month. [Adweek]\n\nViacom announced at its NewFront it plans to bring the video creator conference VidCon to London next year. It also unveiled a slate of talent deals and content partnerships. [Variety]\n\nAbout Us\n\nFollow us on Twitter: @wsjCMO, @larakiara, @VranicaWSJ, @alexbruell,@BenMullin, @srabil, @asharma\n\nSubscribe to our morning newsletter, delivered straight to your inbox, at http://on.wsj.com/CMOTodaySignup.\n\nWrite to Lara O\u2019Reilly at lara.oreilly@wsj.com", "company": "facebook", "authors": ["Lara O Reilly", "Lara.Oreilly Wsj.Com"], "tokens": ["good", "morning", ".", "facebook", "\u2019", "s", "f8", "annual", "developer", "conference", "takes", "place", "today", "and", "wednesday", "in", "san", "jose", ".", "the", "social", "network", "restricted", "developer"